═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CRITICAL — NON-NEGOTIABLE LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS DOC TYPES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The other 3 doc types (EI, RS, DEG/EG) exposed specific annexure converter 
bugs and mapper bugs that repeatedly cost weeks of debugging. NONE of these 
bugs are to be reintroduced in BENOC. Explicit rules:

1. ANNEXURE MAPPER — reuse existing implementation as-is
   Adopt the identity resolver from EI injection / latest RS mapper WITHOUT 
   rewriting. That mapper already handles:
   - Descriptor stripping
   - Identity pooling from material_name, candidates, filename, title, supplier
   - Exact normalized match → 0.99 auto-accept
   - Candidate normalized match → 0.99 auto-accept
   - Token containment fallback → 0.90
   - Partial family containment → 0.90
   - Distinctive-token overlap scoring
   - Filename fallback when body extraction empty
   - Negative-pair protection
   - Auto-accept without user confirmation blocking
   
   Do NOT rebuild. Import and reuse the existing resolver. Only add BENOC-
   specific vocabulary (API names, license document types, stability file 
   patterns).

2. ANNEXURE CONVERTER — no bugs from prior converters
   Explicit prohibitions based on documented past failures:
   
   a) Multi-page extraction MUST process every page of every PDF.
      Reject the pattern where only page 1 is read. Rasterize all pages, 
      run claude_vision on each, merge results. Later pages OVERRIDE page-1 
      defaults when they contain real numeric evidence or material identity. 
      Concatenate raw_text across pages.
   
   b) JSON parsing MUST tolerate malformed LLM output.
      Every LLM response passes through a safe_json_parse that:
      - Strips markdown fences
      - Locates first-brace to last-brace
      - Falls back to bracket for arrays
      - Wraps bare arrays as {extracted_items: [...], schema_repaired: true}
      - Never raises
      - Returns default {} on total failure
   
   c) Bulk processing MUST isolate each annexure.
      - Reset all state between annexures
      - Unique temp file paths (include index or UUID)
      - Per-annexure try/except; one failure never corrupts the next
      - Retry once on parse failure before marking _error=true
      - Handle rate limits with exponential backoff + jitter
      - Unicode normalize filenames and responses
   
   d) Schema consistency — every extracted annexure has stable top-level 
      structure. No bare lists at top level. Consistency guards downgrade 
      contradictory outputs (Yes with null limit, Yes with source=not_mentioned).
   
   e) Filename fallback for material_name/document identity — apply ONLY 
      when body extraction returns empty. Never override valid body extraction 
      with filename inference.

3. STP EXTRACTION DEPTH — SUMMARY ONLY
   The approved BE NOC document uses summary-level specification tables 
   (Sr.No | Test | Specifications), NOT full test-method extraction. STPs 
   are 40+ pages each. Extract:
   - STP document title and applicable product
   - STP number and version
   - Summary list of tests covered
   - Reference to attached full STP as annexure
   Do NOT extract sample preparation procedures, chromatographic conditions, 
   mobile phase composition, wavelength, flow rate, or system suitability 
   from STPs. Those live in the annexure PDF; the main document just 
   references them.

